	<section>
<h2 id="sec3">Artistry</h2>
        <figure>
            <img src="images/logo.png" alt="BLACKPINK">
            <figcaption>BLACKPINK Official Logo</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p> Blackpink's music has been characterized as primarily EDM and pop with elements of hip hop and rap,[147][148] although they have incorporated a variety of other genres in their discography, such as R&B, Arabic music, ballad and rock.[149][150][151] They tend to feature bass drops frequently in their songs, especially immediately preceding the chorus, which some publications consider part of their characteristic sound.[152] Vocally, Blackpink's music has been described as combining fierce and bold rapping with frequent use of an "edgy" singing style.[153][154] Jisoo explained in an interview with Rolling Stone that the members are "involved from the beginning" in their creative process, from "building the blocks" to "adding this or that feeling" and "exchanging feedback".[155]</p>

        <p>Early in their career, Blackpink stated that they wanted to emulate labelmate 2NE1 and "show [their] own unique color".[156] Blackpink has cited various other artists as their musical influences, including Lady Gaga,[157] Ariana Grande,[158] Cardi B and Selena Gomez.[159]</p>
            
        <h4>Concept and lyrical themes</h4>
            <p>Blackpink's concept is represented by their group name; the "black" side represents their more mature, "girl crush" image, while the "pink" side represents their more cute and colorful image.[160] In an interview with Jimmy Kimmel, Rosé explained that the group feels that "there's two colors that represented us the most 'cause we're very girly but at the same time we're very savage too," naming their song "Pretty Savage" as the song that described them best because "it kind of goes with 'black pink.'"[161] The group's lyrics generally address themes of independence, female empowerment, breakups, and toxic relationships, as well as summer romances.[162][163]</p>
            
            <p>Since their debut, Blackpink have emerged as a prominent act in K-pop and have been labeled the "biggest girl group in the world",[164][165][166] "biggest K-pop girl band on the planet",[167] and "K-pop Queens".[16] Insider wrote that they "[burst] onto the K-pop scene with a set of singles that set them on a path to becoming the ambassadors of the 'girl crush' concept", encapsulating "confidence, sexiness, and inspirational assurance, in the K-pop landscape."[168] Billboard called them "K-pop's most visible representatives" of girl crush following their 2018 release "Ddu-Du Ddu-Du".[169] In South Korea, they ranked first on Forbes Korea Power Celebrity 40 list in 2019, third in 2020, and second in 2021.[170] International media outlets such as Forbes, Billboard and The Hollywood Reporter have recognized the group's popularity and contribution toward spreading the Korean Wave globally.[16][171][172][173] Blackpink were cited by Rolling Stone as an exception to the stereotype that most successful K-pop acts in the United States are boy groups.[174]</p>
            
            <p>The group was also credited as one of the two acts leading Korean music industry growth by the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry (IFPI).[175] Blackpink have appeared in multiple power listings. They were the first girl group to make Forbes' 30 Under 30 Asia[171][176] and were named to the 2019 Time 100 Next list of rising stars, credited with "heralding a new era of Korean acts stepping past language barriers to play global stages" when they became the first K-pop group to perform at Coachella, the world's largest music festival.[177][178][179] In another first for a Korean act, Blackpink were named the biggest musicians in the world in the month of October 2020 in Bloomberg's Pop Star Power Ranking.[180] People magazine included Blackpink on their list of women changing the music industry.[181] They became the third girl group in history to cover Rolling Stone, after the Spice Girls and Destiny's Child, when they covered the magazine's June 2022 issue.[182]</p>
            
            <p>Especially in South Korea, Blackpink's influence also extends to fashion.[193] Each member has served as global ambassadors for different luxury brands: Jisoo for Dior,[194] Jennie for Chanel,[195] Rosé for Yves Saint Laurent,[196] and Lisa for Bulgari and Celine.[197][198] Additionally, Blackpink have been credited for drawing international attention to South Korean hanbok through their modern re-interpretations of the traditional costume in their "How You Like That" music video and performances.[199][200] The group considers fashion to be an important part of their public image, with Jennie telling Elle magazine that it "definitely empowers us as much as music does" and Rosé describing it as inseparable from their music.[164] Their style has been noted for blending group uniformity with individual tastes.[201]</p>                  
